description: From Middle English inland, inlond, from Old English inland, equivalent to in- +‎ land. Compare West Frisian ynlân (“inland”), German Inland (“inland”), Danish indland (“inland”), Swedish inland (“inland”), Norwegian innland (“inland”). Compare also Dutch binnenland.

adjectives.description: inland (comparative more inland, superlative most inland)

entries.meaning: Within the land; relatively remote from the ocean or from open water; interior.
Limited to the land, or to inland routes; within the seashore boundary; not passing on, or over, the sea
Confined to a country or state; domestic; not foreign.

adverbs.description: inland (comparative more inland, superlative most inland)

entries.meaning: Into, or towards, the interior of the land, away from the coast.
The interior part of a country.
